When would you want to use a remote repository rather than keeping all your work local?

    So you can access the matrial on a diferent divice and if your computer breakes you can use a different computer.

Why might you want to always pull changes manually rather than having Git 
automatically stay up-to-date with your remote repository?

    You would want to pull changes manualy so you can controll what you are going to pull rather than Github guessing.

Describe the differences between forks, clones, and branches.  When would you
use one instead of another?

    You fork someone else's repository.
	You make a branch in your own repository as to add new features without disturbing production 
	code.
	You clone any repository that is remote or on your own machine. This creates a copy of that repository. 

What is the benefit of having a copy of the last known state of the remote
stored locally?

    The benefit is that you can always go back if you are offline. So you do not need internet access to fix something.

How would you collaborate without using Git or GitHub?  What would be easier,
and what would be harder?

    I don't know of another way to collaborate without using git ot github

When would you want to make changes in a separate branch rather than directly in
master?  What benefits does each approach have?

    You would make changes to a branch if you want to change a spesific thing in the brnanch. You would make the change in the master if you want to makein pernament. 
